{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18662"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18662"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.03,0,0.05,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62956"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"7147"},{"type":"tags","id":"10355"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum is divided into distinct lobes by major fissures. These lobes have different embryological origins and functional roles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the major lobes of the cerebellum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior, posterior, and flocculonodular lobes","Rostral, caudal, and lateral lobes","Primary, secondary, and tertiary lobes","Superior, middle, and inferior lobes","Vermis, paravermis, and hemispheric lobes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum is divided into three major lobes: the \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior, posterior, and flocculonodular lobes (image)\u003C/strong\u003E. The primary fissure separates the anterior and posterior lobes, while the posterolateral fissure separates the posterior and flocculonodular lobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERostral, caudal, and lateral lobes\u003C/strong\u003E - While these are directional terms, they are not used to name cerebellar lobes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary, secondary, and tertiary lobes\u003C/strong\u003E - This numerical naming system is not used for cerebellar lobes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior, middle, and inferior lobes\u003C/strong\u003E - This terminology is not used for cerebellar divisions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVermis, paravermis, and hemispheric lobes\u003C/strong\u003E - These terms describe medial-to-lateral divisions rather than the main lobes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach lobe has distinct functions: the anterior lobe controls posture and gait, the posterior lobe coordinates skilled voluntary movements, and the flocculonodular lobe regulates balance and vestibular function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cerebellum has three main lobes: anterior, posterior, and flocculonodular","The primary fissure separates the anterior and posterior lobes","The posterolateral fissure separates the posterior and flocculonodular lobes","Each lobe has distinct functions in motor control and balance"],"references":["